{ Hi and welcome to this Quickstarter!  This is a part of an update that I am doing now, in June 2020, as this course is about to go in print as a physical book.  Let me tell you a few words about how I think you should use it and based on what factors I chose the lines for it!  Back when I was creating it, Quickstarters weren't a thing yet. But, considering I have been doing my best to make the process of studying my repertoires as enjoyable and convenient as possible, I thought it wouldn't hurt to add it.  Since this work was published, I've made a few more courses that have already been received very positively, and have prepared a few more ones that are yet to be published. Besides shameless self-advertising you might see implied in the last phrase, this also means I have gained tons of experience with Chessable, as well as with the Quickstarters.  My first QS, done for the Accelerated Queen's Indian repertoire, was good in many ways, but it was too large.  I would simply include a few core lines from each chapter, and considering there are more than a dozen chapters in that course, the QC turned out 50 lines long. A bit too much, in my opinion.  My second QS, done for my course on the Dynamic Italian for White, which is about to be published soon, saw a slightly different strategy. I picked some key mainlines as well as sidelines that are simply bad, as they are rather popular. I've included typical mistakes in the QC. And, I've also tried including lines from each chapter, that's what most authors do.  For this QS, though, I have decided to break this tradition. I have ignored most chapters, such as one on King's Gambit, Vienna game, sidelines, etc. I have only added lines from a few key chapters, as I believe the point of the Quickstarter is to get you up and running quickly - quite logical, isn't it? - so it's not worth discussing sidelines here. After all, they are covered in the actual chapters, feel free to take a look!  So, I've given some lines from the Italian here, a few from Scotch and the Scotch four knights, a couple from the Exchange Ruy and the 5.d3 Ruy and a few from the Open Spanish, the heart of this repertoire.  I am offering two solutions vs the Spanish - 6...exd4 and 6...Be7. While the latter is a much more serious theoretical option, I have included 6...exd4 in the Quickstarter. My reasoning behind this was very simple: if you are a player of 1800 and below, or even 2000 and below, most likely you will be using the line 6...exd4. So, that's what you need.  If you are a stronger player or a lower-rated one who wishes to play 6...Be7, then you don't need any shortcuts, feel free to just start with the actual chapter!  I hope such a way of organizing this QS makes sense, and while some may be unhappy about it, I think most users will find it practical, as the Italian/Scotch/Scotch 4 knights/Ruy is 95% of what they encounter in their games!  Good luck, dear students!  Cheers,  Yuriy }
