1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4
{ I have decided to cover the Scotch Four Knights because this is something club players face a lot. The simplicity of the arising positions and straightforwardness of White's plan largely contributed to the popularity of this variation. So did some good books such as Keep It Simple, published by fellow Chessable author Sielecki. I have decided to come up with a slightly offbeat approach. This approach should enable you to get a rather complex and fighting position where White is unable to play the first 15 moves on autopilot but would rather need to solve some new tasks. I can't promise an advantage for Black, but we will try to present our opponent with some new challenges. }
4... Bb4 { This suits our task best. } 5. d5
{ This might seem very reasonable to many players because it gains space. This closed position is similar to the Nimzo-Indian and, as we will see, the bishop pair doesn't matter here. Black can try to play a long-term game against White's worse structure. This is a very unpleasant scenario for a 1. e4 player to face ! }
5... Ne7 6. Bd3 d6 7. O-O Bxc3 8. bxc3 Nd7
{ I think that this is a great choice to play for a win where your opponent has long-term weaknesses. His space advantage matters less after trading some pieces, while White's weaknesses become more noticeable. It is interesting to know that this position has only been reached in one game ! I will give a few possible variations on how the game can develop, but also strongly suggest that you study this typical Nimzo-Indian structure that arises in the so-called Huebner Wall variation. Black would like to push f7-f5, while White can try g3-f4. We will first take a look at what happens if White plays without a plan. After that, we'll study some variations which seem to be more active for White. However, I've realized that it's near impossible for White to be able to play g3-f4 ! So these seemingly active variations are actually Black ! }
9. Be3
{ This might look like a normal developing move, but in closed positions, it's important to choose the correct squares for your pieces. The bishop isn't doing much on e3, just like it wouldn't on d2, b2 or a3. And importantly, White is not pursuing any plan, which makes matters even worse. }
9... O-O 10. c4
{ This will demonstrate Black's plan, provided White is passive. } 10... b6
{ This is a very important move. It prepares Nc5 and prevents variations with Bxc5 where we need to take with the d-pawn. Taking with the b-pawn only strengthens our center and opens up the b-file. }
11. Qe2 Nc5 12. Rab1 Nxd3
{ Our plan includes this and f5. In some other lines, I was afraid that f5 would be met with d3-d4 !, which is impossible here. That is why it's such a timely decision. }
13. cxd3 f5
{ It's obvious that Black seized the initiative. The f-file is opening up and Black's pieces are ideally placed. The knight can go to g6, the bishop to g4. Then we'll develop our queen and the other rook, for instance with Rf7-Raf8. }
