1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3
{ Now it's time to consider this little pawn move. Just as 6. d3, it is usually used by people, who would like to play calm positional chess and avoid analyzing forcing lines, which we study later in this course. However, everything comes at price - Black gets to develop in a very smooth way, and I am about to explain the subtleties of the setup now. }
5... d6 6. c3 g6
{ This is the reason, why 5. d3 is less dangerous than its 'older sibling', the 6. d3 line  (which we don't face though with our repertoire)  . Why is this move so good and so important ? Because in the very main Ruy Lopez very often Black plays Bf8-e7 and then tries to defend his king with such manoeuvres as Rf8-e8, Be7-f8, then g7-g6 and Bf8-g7 ! Count, how many tempi did we just save ? This is why I think that 5,d3 gives Black such an easy game. The next moves don't matter that much - White can play Nbd2, O-O, Re1, Nf1, Ng3,h3 - these are all typical Ruy Lopez moves to get more presense on the kingside. We will play Bg7, O-O, then a few options are possible. Let's proceed with the line to discuss them soon. }
7. Nbd2 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1 b5
{ Now this is the interesting point. White can retreat his bishop to two different squares - and we will react differently, too ! }
10. Bc2
{ Please, pay attention that there is also a move Bb3 and consult other chapters to cover this one - it's very important here, as we react in a different way to the other retreat! }
10... Nb8
{ It is a typical Breyer regroupment, which I really like as a person, who has played around 20 classical games in Breyer so far to never lose one, even to many GMs. This setup is so flexible ! Your next moves include Nbd7, Bb7, Re8, then often pawn to c5, pawn to d5. The point of removing the knight is that on c6 it was not doing much - it couldn't go to many squares and was also obstructing the bishop on b7. And now from d7 it can often go to c5 or b6, for example. }
11. d4 Nbd7 12. Nf1 Bb7 13. Ng3 Re8
{ Is funnily a direct transposition to the Breyer variation of the Ruy Lopez, when White is two tempi down! That is because d2-d4 was played in two moves, he also has not managed to get h2-h3 in Black already installed his bishop on g7 and did it without losing the time. You can consider the simplifying d6-d5 break on the next move, for instance. Or play a tense game with c7-c5, keep the tension going. }
