10. Bxe2 d5
{ It's crucial to fight for the center. The position is not as dull as it seems, and White could try to get an edge by playing c3-c4  (preventing d7-d5)  if we play passively. Bf3 !, keeping an eye on our queenside, could make our life very tough afterward. But after the simple 10... d5 ! we are doing great. A simple plan includes Bf5 to attack the c2-pawn, or Be6 and c7-c6 to defend the d5-pawn once again and prevent ideas with c3-c4. We can then also develop the dark-squared bishop to e7, d6 or c5 and then castle. It also makes a whole lot of sense to not castle short, you can play f7-f6 followed by Kf7 or castle long in order to keep the king closer to the center. }
