{ I have chosen this forcing move and not the position and symmetrical 4... Bb4 for several reasons.  1  After 4... Bb4 there is more theory.  2  4... Nd4 is more likely to surprise your opponents where they are less aware of the variations.  3  I like to prevent opponents from getting the kind of position they want !   4. Bb5 clearly indicates that White wants a positional struggle with all the pieces on the board, so we are trying to go for something a bit more tactical. It is possible for White to avoid tactical lines here, but then it is much easier for us to equalize on the spot. If White dares to enter complications we get excellent attacking chances and are happy to sacrifice material for a tremendous initiative in a lot of lines. }
5. Nxd4
{ Provided that you are unhappy with simplifications, this is a sad move to face. White manages to trade numerous pieces by force. Well, sometimes this happens. }
5... exd4 6. e5 dxc3 7. exf6 Qxf6 8. dxc3 Qe5+
{ 8...Bc5  is a possibility you can also take a look at. We concentrate on another move in this course. }
9. Qe2 { White would usually trade queens here, but 9. Be2 is also possible. }
9... Qxe2+
{ Now some concrete moves don't matter at all and whether White takes with his king or bishop, the character of the game remains the same. We will try to discuss a few typical ideas and our setup while going through the next ballpark variation. }
10. Bxe2 d5
{ It's crucial to fight for the center. The position is not as dull as it seems, and White could try to get an edge by playing c3-c4  (preventing d7-d5)  if we play passively. Bf3 !, keeping an eye on our queenside, could make our life very tough afterward. But after the simple 10... d5 ! we are doing great. A simple plan includes Bf5 to attack the c2-pawn, or Be6 and c7-c6 to defend the d5-pawn once again and prevent ideas with c3-c4. We can then also develop the dark-squared bishop to e7, d6 or c5 and then castle. It also makes a whole lot of sense to not castle short, you can play f7-f6 followed by Kf7 or castle long in order to keep the king closer to the center. }
11. Bf4 c6 12. O-O-O
{ A good move. It objectively remains equal after both O-O and O-O-O, but castling short somehow strikes me as a demonstration of misunderstanding and of a lack of basic endgame culture. Although I shouldn't be too harsh, as the evaluation doesn't change a lot regardless of what both sides do. It's a solid position for both. }
12... Be6 13. Rhe1 O-O-O
{ We again play Bd6, swap bishops, play Rhe8 and Kc7 to reach a simple and equal position. A draw is very likely, but both can play for a win if they want to. }
