1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6
{ This move signifies the Exchange Ruy Lopez. Its idea is to double the Black pawns, then play d4 at some point, which will trade the e5-pawn and create a position when both sides have two pawn islands. Since Black's extra doubled pawn on the queenside isn't as important, White sort of has an 'extra' pawn on e4. This is noticeable for the whole game, unlike the doubled pawns on c6 and c7. White would like to trade pieces and win the endgame thanks to his extra kingside pawn. However, Black has his own trumps, such as a pair of bishops. }
4... dxc6 5. d4
{ Please, take a look at this line first to understand the ideas behind Qf6 in the main line. This is the way people used to play back in the day. The idea is very simple: trade all the pieces and win the pawn endgame. White wants to castle queenside, so that 1  when he advances the pawn on the kingside, his king is safe, as it is not being opened up. 2  it's faster to get to the center from c1 rather than g1. However, later such ideas were neutralized and people switched to 5. O-O }
5... exd4 6. Nxd4
{ Is not a good idea - now White will simply get the same type of positions, but lose the right to castle. }
6... c5 7. Ne2
{ It could have gone anywhere, Black would trade queens anyway to deprive White of castling. }
7... Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 Bd7
{ And the White king is an issue for him, of course, because the board is yet full of pieces, which means it will be getting attacked and disturbed all the time. }
