{ In my opinion, 5. O-O Be7 6. Bxc6 is quite a reasonable line, because White wins a tempo - the black bishop goes to e7, and later it has to go to d6. However, this line is not possible within our repertoire, as we play Open Spanish and meet 5. O-O with Nxe4. That is why we will study the 5. Bxc6 line only and I believe Black should be very happy to see this variation. }
5... dxc6 6. d3
{ White's idea is to calmly develop, castle, go Nd2-Nc4, remove the f3-knight and prepare the eventual f2-f4. I don't think we need to know concrete stuff here. However, I would like to introduce you to some plans. Why did White take on c6 on move 5, not move 4? How is this line different from the Exchange Spanish ? The answer is our f6-knight. Now that it's developed to f6, it is rather misplaced, and we will need to improve it. The best square for it evenutally is d4, so the route is Nd7, then it goes to f8-e6 or c5-e6 to end up on d4. However, it stands well on e6, too, as it prevents f2-f4 ideas. Our bishop belongs to d6, because it helps protect the e5-pawn. Let's see how Black develops, keeping these ideas in mind. Again, forcing lines don't exist here - it's understanding that matters. }
