{ Of course, White can try to go d2-d3 fast, but in my opinion, this is quite inconsistent with the move Qe2. What is the whole idea behind Qe2 ? I think it's reasonable only if White tries to keep the pawn on d2, go Rd1 and then c2-c3 followed by the quick d2-d4. In this case his rook is quite annoyingly aimed at the Black queen. On the other hand, if White never plays d4, his setup is sort of toothless. }
7. c3
{ I think this is the line we must concentrate on, as 5. Qe2 is a very rare line and I want to provide you with general understanding of it, not with the coverage of every single little move order, which you'll never see in your games. }
7... O-O
{ As I had said, changing the roles of the queen and the rook could be beneficial for White, because sometimes the Black queen might be hit over the d-file. However, this setup has cons as well. One of them is that it's easier for Black to go d7-d5 right now and play in Marshall Gambit style. The point is that in many lines when White captures on e5 with the queen, his queen is getting rather exposed. Now White had tried two moves - 8. O-O and 8. d3 }
8. O-O
{ Another popular move. White keeps his options open, he can play either d3 or d4. }
8... d5
{ I like this active approach. I think many other moves, such as 8..d6, are possible, but we follow the same setup for the sake of clarity and simplicity. }
9. exd5 { And now follows an idea new to us } 9... e4
{ White has to take on c6, as retreating allows for Bg4, when the queen has no squares to go to. }
10. Ne1 Bg4 { Suddenly wins the queen ! } *

